    "statement": "Let $P$ be a point on the parabola $y^2=4ax$, where $a>0$. The normal to the parabola at $P$ meets the $x$-axis at a point $Q$. The area of the triangle $PFQ$, where $F$ is the focus of the parabola, is $120$. If the slope $m$ of the normal and $a$ are both positive integers, then the pair $(a,m)$ is\n\n(A) $(2,3)$ ┬Ę (B) $(1,3)$ ┬Ę (C) $(2,4)$ ┬Ę (D) $(3,4)$",
    "answer": "$\\boxed{(a,m)=(2,3)}$ \\; ŌĆö option (A).",
    "trap": "The normal to $y^2=4ax$ in slope form is $y=mx-2am-am^3$, so at the foot $P$ the slope of the normal is $m$, not the parameter $t$. Writing $P$ as $(at^2,2at)$ and then using $m=t$ (the tangent parameter) corrupts every subsequent length. Here $m=-t$, giving $P=(am^2,-2am)$; the sign matters for locating $Q$ and for the area to come out a clean $a^2m(m^2+1)$.",
